Here's the proper approach using MAUI's lifecycle events and `Preferences`:

**In `App.xaml.cs`** — hook into lifecycle events:

```csharp
protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
{
    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

    window.Deactivated += (s, e) =>
        WeakReferenceMessenger.Default.Send(new AppBackgroundMessage());

    window.Activated += (s, e) =>
        WeakReferenceMessenger.Default.Send(new AppForegroundMessage());

    return window;
}
```

**Define simple messages:**

```csharp
public class AppBackgroundMessage { }
public class AppForegroundMessage { }
```

**In your notes page ViewModel:**

```csharp
public partial class NotesViewModel : ObservableObject, IRecipient<AppBackgroundMessage>
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private string draftText = string.Empty;

    public NotesViewModel()
    {
        // Restore draft on creation
        DraftText = Preferences.Default.Get("draft_note", string.Empty);

        WeakReferenceMessenger.Default.RegisterAll(this);
    }

    // Save draft when app backgrounds
    public void Receive(AppBackgroundMessage message)
    {
        Preferences.Default.Set("draft_note", DraftText);
    }

    // Call this when the user explicitly saves/discards
    public void ClearDraft()
    {
        Preferences.Default.Remove("draft_note");
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`Preferences`** is ideal for small text. For large drafts, use `FileSystem.AppDataDirectory` with a file instead.
- **`Deactivated`** fires on backgrounding (covers home button, app switch, phone lock).
- **`WeakReferenceMessenger`** (from `CommunityToolkit.Mvvm`) decouples the lifecycle from the VM cleanly.
- Also save in `OnDisappearing` of the page as a safety net.
